	&lt;strong&gt;I agree with the inspection results and would like to make other comments.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	These were the following actions given to me on the day of inspection: - A cross contamination issue - mushrooms (raw) and raw meat were mixed with salad in the fridge - no excuses for this - I have since circulated a read and sign and even though the shelves are labelled, I asked staff to put fresher labels on each shelf and to the side of the shelves to make it very clear as we have a lot of agency supporting with food/cooking as well. - There was no kitchen spray in the kitchen at the time of the inspection - staff must have used it and just not replaced it - I did challenge this as we keep our COSHH all in the laundry room and staff know to get more from there but it was put down as an action - I put a new bottle of spray in there on the day of inspection and again, added this to the read and sign Extractor fan filters needed a clean - since been done, I have added this as a weekly check on the cleaning checklist and also bought more new ones To pest proof the internal and external doors due to having involvement with Preventapest (previous issues with rats) - this has been logged on our maintenance system and my maintenance tech has already been out to assess. Peeling paint on the ceiling in one area of the kitchen - this was already on our maintenance system, and I have since chased this work - should be completed next week - awaiting a date&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div&gt;
	The establishment has been thoroughly cleaned and procedures are in place to ensure cleanliness is maintained.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
	A new management system has been implemented.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
	Staff have been trained/given instruction/are under revised supervisory arrangements.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
	An inspection was carried out on 20th June 2022 as a result as we understand of a complaint received by Environmental Health. A post inspection report was received dated 5th July 2022. A revisit in between this was carried out on 23rd June where it was acknowledged that a much better standard of cleaning had been achieved. The kitchen was voluntarily closed on the 20th in order to deep clean. We would like to address the main issues in the inspection report:&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
	Food Hygiene &amp;amp; Safety Procedures: We note that at the inspection you observed there were some partially or uncovered foods within the refrigerator with a potential for cross contamination.This has been addressed and all staff have been reminded of the need for this to be stored appropriately. This has also covered appropriate labelling to ensure that robust stock rotation is maintained so food does not pass its in house use by dates. Under this it was also raised that an employee did not have a snood to prevent contamination from facial hair. This was addressed immediately and whilst he tendered his resignation in July 2022&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
	we note that any future employees will be required to wear appropriate clothing and facial coverings. We would like to take this opportunity to advise that all kitchen staff wear hair appropriately tied and hairnets and this includes any KP accessing collection. Structural/Cleaning Issues: It was noted that there were cleaning issues required at the time of your visit and all the items although not exhaustive have been rectified. A new cleaning schedule has been introduced and this is documented in the SFBB. The products are covered by are revised COSHH risk assessment. At the time of visit the dishwasher was broken and this was rectified immediately. That said we acknowledge that ther needs to be a contingency plan in the event of this happening in the future and this is documented in our revised SFBB.The wall in the middle kitchen which posed a physical risk of contamination has been replaced with a non porous easily cleanable surface. Also the remainde of the&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
	kitchen has been decorated .&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
	Confidence in Management/Control Procedures: Our SFBB has been completely reviewed which address all points raised and a complete review to ensure all staff are aware of responsibilities commensurate to their role.All food handlers have received training and two employees have level 3 food hygiene training.We can confirm that no member of staff will be supervising the kitchen without the appropriate level 3 and refresher training for all be provided and documented. This is reflected in the reviewed SFBB manual. This is as part of compliance with our Hygiene Improvement Notice. Finally on this element receipt of deliveries are now checked by drivers on arrival and checked by the receiving member of staff.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
	The conditions found at the time of the inspection were not typical of the normal conditions maintained at the establishment and arose because it was extremely unfortunate that at the time of the initial inspection the kitchen had not been deep cleaned after the end of the very busy Fathers Day shift. We accept this is unacceptable and staff have been reminded that they do not leave shift however busy until all has been cleaned in readiness. We deeply regret where we found ourselves but wish to reassure you all recommendations and above have been implemented in the aim for the re score. We have always prided ourselves on being a good quality venue and recognised in the village as going over and above for customers in all aspects. We hope to return to this position. We thank you for all your&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
	advice and support to date.&lt;/div&gt;
